<ArticleLayout
  title="Small Laundry Storage: What to Check Before Buying Organisers"
  description="Before buying organisers for a small laundry, check floor space, machine clearance, drying needs, baskets, shelving, doors, rental limits and whether storage will block daily use."
  category="Laundry"
  date="Updated July 2026"
  readingTime="8 minute read"
  showAffiliateDisclosure={false}
  image="/images/laundry.webp"
  imageAlt="A practical laundry room with warm finishes, baskets and tidy everyday storage"
>
  <p>Small laundries can become crowded quickly.</p>
  <p>
    A narrow room, laundry cupboard, apartment laundry or bathroom-laundry combination may
    need to handle washing, drying, baskets, cleaning products, towels, pet items, linen
    overflow and household supplies in very little space. When the room is already tight,
    the wrong organiser can make it harder to move, open doors, use the washing machine or
    dry clothes properly.
  </p>
  <p>
    Before buying shelves, baskets, trolleys, wall racks or over-machine storage, it is worth
    checking what the small laundry actually needs to do.
  </p>
  <p>The aim is not to fill every gap. The aim is to keep the laundry usable.</p>
  <p>
    For broader laundry planning, see our main guide:
    <a href="/guides/laundry-storage-what-to-measure-and-check-before-you-buy/">
      Laundry Storage: What to Measure and Check Before You Buy</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Start with the real small laundry problem</h2>
  <p>A small laundry may feel frustrating for several reasons.</p>
  <p>The problem may be:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>not enough floor space</li>
    <li>nowhere to sort dirty clothes</li>
    <li>no practical drying area</li>
    <li>cleaning products scattered around the tub</li>
    <li>a washing machine or dryer blocking access</li>
    <li>doors that open into the working space</li>
    <li>shelves that are too high or too shallow</li>
    <li>baskets sitting in walkways</li>
    <li>no clear place for towels or linen overflow</li>
    <li>a rental layout that cannot be permanently changed</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Different problems need different storage choices.</p>
  <p>
    If baskets are blocking the floor, shelves may not be the first answer. If drying is the
    main issue, another storage basket will not solve it. If cleaning products are crowded
    around the tub, a small caddy or shelf may help more than a large unit.
  </p>
  <p>The first step is to decide what is actually making the laundry hard to use.</p>

  <h2>Keep floor space as the priority</h2>
  <p>In a small laundry, floor space is working space.</p>
  <p>You need enough room to:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>stand in front of the washing machine</li>
    <li>open the machine door or lid</li>
    <li>load and unload washing</li>
    <li>move a basket safely</li>
    <li>access the laundry tub</li>
    <li>open cupboards or room doors</li>
    <li>use a drying rack if needed</li>
    <li>clean around the machines</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Before buying any floor-standing storage, measure the walkway and door clearance.
  </p>
  <p>
    A trolley, hamper or shelf may fit on paper but still make the laundry awkward if it
    blocks movement. In very small laundries, clear floor space can be more useful than
    another organiser.
  </p>
  <p>If a product makes the room harder to move through, it is probably the wrong solution.</p>

  <h2>Measure the washing machine area</h2>
  <p>The washing machine usually controls the whole laundry layout.</p>
  <p>Before buying storage around it, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>machine width</li>
    <li>machine depth</li>
    <li>machine height</li>
    <li>space beside the machine</li>
    <li>space behind the machine</li>
    <li>hose and tap position</li>
    <li>power point location</li>
    <li>whether the machine moves during spin cycles</li>
    <li>door or lid clearance</li>
    <li>access for cleaning and maintenance</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Top loaders need clear space above the machine so the lid can open properly. Front
    loaders need clear space in front so the door can open and washing can be loaded easily.
  </p>
  <p>
    Do not place shelves, baskets or trolleys where they block access to taps, hoses,
    filters, power points or the machine door.
  </p>
  <p>
    Storage around the machine should make laundry easier, not make the appliance harder to
    use.
  </p>

  <h2>Check the dryer situation</h2>
  <p>If the laundry has a dryer, check the space carefully before adding storage.</p>
  <p>Measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>dryer width</li>
    <li>dryer depth</li>
    <li>dryer height</li>
    <li>door swing</li>
    <li>space around the dryer</li>
    <li>power point access</li>
    <li>ventilation needs</li>
    <li>whether nearby shelves block airflow or access</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Be cautious with storage above, around or near dryers. Follow the appliance
    manufacturer's guidance for clearance, ventilation and placement.
  </p>
  <p>
    A small laundry can become hot, damp or difficult to use if storage blocks airflow or
    makes the dryer hard to access.
  </p>
  <p>
    If drying is already a problem, storage should support airflow and access rather than
    crowding the room further.
  </p>

  <h2>Use vertical space carefully</h2>
  <p>Vertical storage can help in a small laundry, but it needs to be practical.</p>
  <p>Possible options include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>shelves above the machine</li>
    <li>freestanding shelving</li>
    <li>narrow wall shelves</li>
    <li>over-door storage</li>
    <li>hanging rails</li>
    <li>compact racks</li>
    <li>baskets on higher shelves</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Before using vertical space, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>whether items will be easy to reach</li>
    <li>whether shelves block machine lids or doors</li>
    <li>whether drilling is allowed</li>
    <li>whether the wall can support the load</li>
    <li>whether the space is damp</li>
    <li>whether stored items could fall</li>
    <li>whether tall storage makes the room feel cramped</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Heavy bottles, large detergent containers and bulky baskets should not be stored so high
    that they are difficult or unsafe to lift down.
  </p>
  <p>
    In small laundries, vertical storage works best for lighter, less frequently used items.
  </p>

  <h2>Be careful with slim trolleys</h2>
  <p>Slim trolleys can look like an easy answer for narrow gaps.</p>
  <p>They may help with:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>detergent</li>
    <li>pegs</li>
    <li>cloths</li>
    <li>stain removers</li>
    <li>small cleaning supplies</li>
    <li>spare laundry items</li>
  </ul>
  <p>But they only work if the gap is genuinely usable.</p>
  <p>Before buying a slim trolley, measure:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>gap width</li>
    <li>gap depth</li>
    <li>gap height</li>
    <li>skirting boards</li>
    <li>hoses or taps</li>
    <li>appliance movement</li>
    <li>whether the trolley can roll out fully</li>
    <li>whether it blocks doors or drawers</li>
    <li>whether it becomes unstable when full</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A trolley squeezed beside a machine may be hard to use if hoses, taps or skirting boards
    block the wheels.
  </p>
  <p>Avoid overloading narrow trolleys with heavy bottles, especially if the trolley feels unstable.</p>

  <h2>Choose baskets that match the space</h2>
  <p>Laundry baskets and hampers can create order, but they can also take over a small room.</p>
  <p>Before buying a hamper, sorter or basket system, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>available floor space</li>
    <li>basket height</li>
    <li>basket width</li>
    <li>carrying comfort</li>
    <li>ventilation</li>
    <li>whether lids need clearance</li>
    <li>whether the basket blocks a door or machine</li>
    <li>whether the household actually sorts washing before laundry day</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A divided laundry sorter may help a family with frequent loads. It may be too large for a
    small apartment laundry.
  </p>
  <p>A compact basket may be better if the laundry is narrow or shared with a bathroom.</p>
  <p>
    Choose a basket system that supports the routine, not one that simply looks organised
    when empty.
  </p>

  <h2>Check drying space before buying storage</h2>
  <p>Small laundries often struggle with drying.</p>
  <p>Before buying more shelves or organisers, check whether drying is the real problem.</p>
  <p>Ask:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Where do wet clothes dry?</li>
    <li>Is there enough airflow?</li>
    <li>Does a drying rack block the laundry?</li>
    <li>Can the rack be stored when folded?</li>
    <li>Does indoor drying create moisture problems?</li>
    <li>Are towels or uniforms regularly left hanging over doors?</li>
    <li>Does the household need a compact drying option?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A large folding airer may not suit a tiny laundry if there is nowhere practical to open
    it.
  </p>
  <p>
    A smaller, portable drying rack may work better if it can be used in another room and
    stored away when not needed.
  </p>
  <p>Do not let storage products reduce the only practical drying area.</p>

  <h2>Keep cleaning products grouped and safe</h2>
  <p>Small laundries often store more cleaning products than they need.</p>
  <p>Before buying caddies, baskets or shelves, group the products you already have.</p>
  <p>Check for:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>empty bottles</li>
    <li>duplicate cleaners</li>
    <li>old stain removers</li>
    <li>leaking products</li>
    <li>products that belong in another room</li>
    <li>items that need safer storage</li>
    <li>bottles that are too tall for shelves</li>
    <li>products that should be stored according to label directions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Cleaning products should be easy to access but not scattered everywhere.</p>
  <p>
    A small caddy, basket or shelf may help if it keeps regularly used products together.
    Avoid buying a large organiser before removing old or duplicate items.
  </p>

  <h2>Think about renters and non-permanent storage</h2>
  <p>Renters need to be careful with small laundry storage.</p>
  <p>Be cautious with:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>drilling</li>
    <li>adhesive hooks</li>
    <li>wall-mounted drying racks</li>
    <li>fixed shelves</li>
    <li>cabinet modifications</li>
    <li>racks that mark doors</li>
    <li>products that rely on one unusual layout</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Renter-friendly options may include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>freestanding shelves</li>
    <li>portable drying racks</li>
    <li>slim trolleys</li>
    <li>removable baskets</li>
    <li>over-door storage that does not damage the door</li>
    <li>non-permanent caddies</li>
    <li>compact hampers</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Adhesive products may still damage paint, tiles, laminate or cabinet finishes when
    removed.
  </p>
  <p>If you rent, choose storage that can move with you where possible.</p>

  <h2>Avoid overcrowding the laundry</h2>
  <p>The biggest mistake in a small laundry is trying to solve every problem with more storage.</p>
  <p>Too many products can create new problems:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>baskets block the floor</li>
    <li>shelves make the room feel cramped</li>
    <li>racks stop doors opening</li>
    <li>trolleys become clutter catchers</li>
    <li>drying space disappears</li>
    <li>cleaning becomes harder</li>
    <li>machines are harder to access</li>
    <li>moisture gets trapped</li>
  </ul>
  <p>A small laundry needs working space as much as storage.</p>
  <p>It is better to have fewer useful storage items than a crowded room full of organisers.</p>

  <h2>Common small laundry storage mistakes</h2>
  <p>Small laundry storage can go wrong when products are chosen too quickly.</p>
  <p>Common mistakes include:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>buying shelves before measuring machine clearance</li>
    <li>blocking the washing machine door or lid</li>
    <li>choosing a hamper that is too large for the room</li>
    <li>buying a slim trolley that cannot roll out properly</li>
    <li>ignoring dryer ventilation or access</li>
    <li>adding storage before removing old cleaning products</li>
    <li>using adhesive products in rentals without considering surface damage</li>
    <li>storing heavy items too high</li>
    <li>buying a drying rack with nowhere to open it</li>
    <li>filling every gap until the laundry is hard to use</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The aim is not to use every centimetre. The aim is to make the laundry easier to use
    every week.
  </p>

  <h2>When not to buy organisers yet</h2>
  <p>You may not need new organisers yet if the real issue is clutter or routine.</p>
  <p>Before buying, check whether the laundry contains:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>empty detergent bottles</li>
    <li>broken baskets</li>
    <li>old cloths</li>
    <li>unused drying racks</li>
    <li>duplicate cleaning products</li>
    <li>items that belong in the garage or bathroom</li>
    <li>towels or linen with no clear home</li>
    <li>pet items mixed with laundry supplies</li>
    <li>products kept just in case</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Removing these items may free up enough space without buying anything.</p>
  <p>
    A small laundry with fewer items can work better than a small laundry with more
    organisers.
  </p>

  <h2>Simple small laundry checklist</h2>
  <p>Before buying storage for a small laundry, check:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>What exact problem am I solving?</li>
    <li>Have I measured the usable floor space?</li>
    <li>Will this block the washing machine door or lid?</li>
    <li>Will this block dryer access or airflow?</li>
    <li>Will doors and cupboards still open?</li>
    <li>Is there enough space to move a basket?</li>
    <li>Is drying space the real problem?</li>
    <li>Is the product easy to clean around?</li>
    <li>Is it suitable for a rental if needed?</li>
    <li>Can it move with me if I rent?</li>
    <li>Will it still work when full?</li>
    <li>Would removing clutter solve the issue first?</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Small laundry storage works best when it protects the working space.</p>
  <p>
    Measure first, keep the floor clear, and choose only the organisers that make washing,
    drying and sorting easier.
  </p>

